00:32:26.562 --> 00:32:28.270
MINA AL ORIABI: Oh,
this was interesting.

00:32:28.270 --> 00:32:30.100
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:30.100 --> 00:32:32.200
MINA AL ORIABI: Yeah,
oh, my god-- so many.

00:32:32.200 --> 00:32:32.920
OK.

00:32:32.920 --> 00:32:34.212
JOYCE BAZ: Which year was this?

00:32:34.212 --> 00:32:36.044
MINA AL ORIABI: Wow, I
should remember this.

00:32:36.044 --> 00:32:37.015
2011, I want to say.

00:32:37.015 --> 00:32:38.500
Yeah, 2011.

00:32:38.500 --> 00:32:43.300
OK, so I interviewed
American officials

00:32:43.300 --> 00:32:46.060
during the Bush administration
times and the Obama times.

00:32:46.060 --> 00:32:50.410
The Bush administration people
were so much more accessible,

00:32:50.410 --> 00:32:52.757
and they had no red lines.

00:32:52.757 --> 00:32:54.340
The only things they
would have is you

00:32:54.340 --> 00:32:56.710
only have the time frame.

00:32:56.710 --> 00:32:58.450
I interviewed Obama
and Kerry, and they

00:32:58.450 --> 00:33:00.730
were so difficult because
Obama-- they wouldn't even

00:33:00.730 --> 00:33:01.970
let me go see him.

00:33:01.970 --> 00:33:04.620
So we did it actually by phone.

00:33:04.620 --> 00:33:05.560
And I said I'll fly.

00:33:05.560 --> 00:33:06.190
I'll come anytime they want.

00:33:06.190 --> 00:33:07.360
And they said no,
and they wanted

00:33:07.360 --> 00:33:08.260
to control it completely.

00:33:08.260 --> 00:33:09.710
And the same was
true actually when

00:33:09.710 --> 00:33:11.860
they-- although Kerry was
more fun because he actually

00:33:11.860 --> 00:33:13.780
was like-- he was trying to be
like we've known each other.

00:33:13.780 --> 00:33:15.002
And I don't know him.

00:33:15.002 --> 00:33:16.710
But with Obama, it
was really controlled.

00:33:16.710 --> 00:33:18.010
It was absolutely controlled.

00:33:18.010 --> 00:33:19.940
The questions were controlled.

00:33:19.940 --> 00:33:22.570
And it was really
disappointing, to be honest.

00:33:22.570 --> 00:33:25.000
With the Bush
administration, I didn't

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:28.030
interview Bush or Cheney, but
I interviewed many others.

00:33:28.030 --> 00:33:30.610
And honestly, the only
constraint would be the time--

00:33:30.610 --> 00:33:31.942
like you have half an hour.

00:33:31.942 --> 00:33:32.650
Do what you want.

00:33:32.650 --> 00:33:34.233
So they really
controlled the message,

00:33:34.233 --> 00:33:37.140
and they believed I worked
in Washington from beginning

00:33:37.140 --> 00:33:40.030
of 2009 to end of 2011.

00:33:40.030 --> 00:33:42.610
They believed that
all we need to do

00:33:42.610 --> 00:33:46.900
is tweet something out or send
you an SMS message saying,

00:33:46.900 --> 00:33:50.920
we're going to send you a speech
that he gave, and that's it.

00:33:50.920 --> 00:33:54.984
I had only one background
briefing with the White House

00:33:54.984 --> 00:33:56.150
the entire time I was there.

00:33:56.150 --> 00:33:57.640
And then I had a couple
of other interviews,

00:33:57.640 --> 00:33:59.380
like with Ben Rhodes
and other people.

00:33:59.380 --> 00:34:01.340
But they really
controlled the message,

00:34:01.340 --> 00:34:03.982
and I think it was to their
detriment internationally.

00:34:08.410 --> 00:34:10.624
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] what
your life would be like

00:34:10.624 --> 00:34:12.124
if your parents
hadn't [INAUDIBLE]..

00:34:12.124 --> 00:34:15.800
What's the picture
that comes to mind?

00:34:15.800 --> 00:34:17.554
MINA AL ORIABI:
Like I said, it's

00:34:17.554 --> 00:34:19.429
the only difference
between me and my cousins

00:34:19.429 --> 00:34:23.600
is that my cousins
didn't leave, and I did.

00:34:23.600 --> 00:34:25.850
But it's also incredible
how resilient they are

00:34:25.850 --> 00:34:27.409
and how much fun they are.

00:34:27.409 --> 00:34:30.116
I saw them recently--
a few of them.

00:34:30.116 --> 00:34:32.699
For people from the Middle East,
like we say, I have a cousin,

00:34:32.699 --> 00:34:34.580
and there's like 45 of them.

00:34:34.580 --> 00:34:37.310
Genuinely, I think I
have like 47 cousins.

00:34:37.310 --> 00:34:40.880
And so it's incredible
how similar we are,

00:34:40.880 --> 00:34:43.040
and I think, again,
that's blood.

00:34:43.040 --> 00:34:43.940
It's incredible.

00:34:43.940 --> 00:34:45.830
Some of my cousins,
I hadn't seen--

00:34:45.830 --> 00:34:48.549
my family was in exile
from 1919 to 2003.

00:34:48.549 --> 00:34:50.090
So I didn't see
family for that long.

00:34:50.090 --> 00:34:52.672
And we went back to
Baghdad at the end of 2003,

00:34:52.672 --> 00:34:55.130
and it was incredible like I'd
seen them just last weekend.

00:34:55.130 --> 00:34:57.046
So that's amazing how
like through inheritance

00:34:57.046 --> 00:34:59.780
and through your parents'
upbringing and so forth,

00:34:59.780 --> 00:35:00.890
you're so similar.

00:35:00.890 --> 00:35:03.657
But life would have been
so much more difficult.

00:35:03.657 --> 00:35:05.990
I definitely wouldn't have
had most of the opportunities

00:35:05.990 --> 00:35:11.450
I've had, but I would say
in terms of confidence,

00:35:11.450 --> 00:35:12.560
I see that in my cousins.

00:35:12.560 --> 00:35:15.560
In terms of aspirations
and so forth,

00:35:15.560 --> 00:35:17.630
it kind of hasn't
beat them down--

00:35:17.630 --> 00:35:20.660
all the craziness
that's happened in Iraq.

00:35:20.660 --> 00:35:22.080
If you're from my
generation, you

00:35:22.080 --> 00:35:24.400
were born in the time when
there's the Iran-Iraq war.

00:35:24.400 --> 00:35:26.857
You finished that, then you
had the Kuwait invasion.

00:35:26.857 --> 00:35:28.940
You finished that, you had
the years of sanctions.

00:35:28.940 --> 00:35:30.440
You finished the
years of sanctions,

00:35:30.440 --> 00:35:31.940
you go into the 2003 war.

00:35:31.940 --> 00:35:33.270
You go into sectarian strife.

00:35:33.270 --> 00:35:36.230
You go into ISIS, and
here we are today.

00:35:36.230 --> 00:35:38.480
So people who are of that
generation-- and especially

00:35:38.480 --> 00:35:40.850
actually, for many men
who are slightly older,

00:35:40.850 --> 00:35:43.970
who actually had to be
drafted into the army,

00:35:43.970 --> 00:35:45.710
it's heartbreaking
because the years

00:35:45.710 --> 00:35:48.860
that they spent being drafted
into these senseless wars.

00:35:48.860 --> 00:35:51.260
So I think if I had stayed
in Iraq and if I was a man,

00:35:51.260 --> 00:35:54.080
it would have been
actually that much worse.

00:35:54.080 --> 00:35:56.621
But at the same time, I
think I would probably

00:35:56.621 --> 00:35:59.120
be very similar in character
because of what my parents have

00:35:59.120 --> 00:35:59.786
instilled in me.

00:36:05.105 --> 00:36:08.075
AUDIENCE: Thank
you for being here.

00:36:08.075 --> 00:36:12.777
I want to go back to a question
regarding [INAUDIBLE] freedom

00:36:12.777 --> 00:36:14.015
of speech.

00:36:14.015 --> 00:36:20.945
[INAUDIBLE] context of the
audiences, and audiences

00:36:20.945 --> 00:36:30.230
[INAUDIBLE] journalists duty
to actually push the boundaries

00:36:30.230 --> 00:36:36.575
[INAUDIBLE] are accustomed
to being exposed to?

00:36:36.575 --> 00:36:38.700
MINA AL ORIABI: Yeah and
we do want certain things.

00:36:38.700 --> 00:36:42.350
So again, it's a fine line,
and it's a negotiation.

00:36:42.350 --> 00:36:44.560
It's a negotiation with
yourself, with your editor.

00:36:44.560 --> 00:36:48.140
There's no external power
that comes and tells you, do,

00:36:48.140 --> 00:36:49.589
do not.

00:36:49.589 --> 00:36:52.130
Definitely, in the Emirates, we
don't live in that landscape.

00:36:52.130 --> 00:36:55.410
I think it's different depending
on the country you're in.

00:36:55.410 --> 00:36:58.330
It's an appreciation
and understanding

00:36:58.330 --> 00:37:01.500
of what would be acceptable,
what isn't acceptable.

00:37:01.500 --> 00:37:05.202
But I mean, to political
powers, not only to audiences.

00:37:05.202 --> 00:37:06.410
So it's your own [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:06.410 --> 00:37:07.420
So it's also your
negotiation, and there

00:37:07.420 --> 00:37:08.230
are things that you choose.

00:37:08.230 --> 00:37:09.400
And you say, no, I'm
going to push on this.

00:37:09.400 --> 00:37:11.230
And we have had
issues like that.

00:37:11.230 --> 00:37:15.100
And to be frank, I mean, touch
wood before I jinx myself.

00:37:15.100 --> 00:37:18.127
Since July 1 until now,
there's not been one thing that

00:37:18.127 --> 00:37:19.960
you've had somebody
turn around and say, no,

00:37:19.960 --> 00:37:21.270
you cannot write that.

00:37:21.270 --> 00:37:23.355
Now does that mean
that we're careful,

00:37:23.355 --> 00:37:24.730
and therefore, we
haven't pushed?

00:37:24.730 --> 00:37:26.439
I think we have pushed
on certain issues.

00:37:26.439 --> 00:37:28.604
I don't know how frequently
you read "The National."

00:37:28.604 --> 00:37:30.100
But we do try,
especially on issues

00:37:30.100 --> 00:37:32.830
that we think are
of public interest,

00:37:32.830 --> 00:37:35.110
and that is kind of
like our guiding force.

00:37:35.110 --> 00:37:37.320
But again, I don't
mean to belittle it,

00:37:37.320 --> 00:37:40.780
but it really isn't that
big a constraint once you

00:37:40.780 --> 00:37:42.721
know what you want to
be out there saying

00:37:42.721 --> 00:37:44.470
and why you're working
in the Middle East.

00:37:44.470 --> 00:37:46.617
I mean, there is a joy
to working from here

00:37:46.617 --> 00:37:48.700
to be able to say there's
a publication coming out

00:37:48.700 --> 00:37:52.420
from the Arab world that
is able to tackle issues--

00:37:52.420 --> 00:37:54.560
social issues but
also political issues,

00:37:54.560 --> 00:37:56.170
questions, certain things.

00:37:56.170 --> 00:37:58.990
Again, not easy-- we're not
going to do irresponsibly.

00:37:58.990 --> 00:38:01.090
But there is a joy in
being able to do that.

